<h2 id=\"raspberry-pi-zero-and-zero-w\">Raspberry Pi Zero and Zero W</h2><p>The incredibly compact Raspberry Pi Zero and Zero W models are known for their minimalist design, and this extends to their LEDs as well.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/pi-zero-w.jpg\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Those Blinking LEDs on Your Raspberry Pi Have Special Meanings\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"728\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/pi-zero-w.jpg 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/pi-zero-w.jpg 970w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"><figcaption><span style=\"white-space: pre-wrap;\">Raspberry Pi Zero W</span></figcaption></figure><p>The most significant difference here is the <strong>absence of the Red (PWR) LED</strong>. The Pi Zero series only features:</p><ul><li><strong>Green LED (ACT):</strong> This is the <em>only</em> status LED. It indicates SD card activity and, importantly, signals boot errors.</li></ul>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
