            </div>
        </div><h2 id=\"conclusion\">Conclusion</h2><p>In conclusion, Raspberry Pi&#x2019;s status LEDs are a surprisingly powerful diagnostic tool, especially for headless setups. </p><p>They allow you to troubleshoot and pinpoint issues without needing a screen or direct access to the Pi. </p><p>It&#x2019;s an intriguing feature that makes the Pi even more versatile for remote projects, as long as you know what the blink codes mean. </p><p>After all, knowing the code is half the battle, without it, those flashing lights might as well be a mystery show.</p><p>You can take your debugging to the next step by <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/use-uart-raspberry-pi/\">adding a UART to your Pi</a> and fetch the debugging data in your computer.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-bookmark-card\"><a class=\"kg-bookmark-container\" href=\"https://itsfoss.com/use-uart-raspberry-pi/\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-content\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-title\">Using a USB Serial Adapter (UART) to Help Debug Raspberry Pi</div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-description\">A UART attached to your Raspberry Pi can help you troubleshoot issues with your Raspberry Pi. Here&#x2019;s what you need to know.</div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-metadata\"><img class=\"kg-bookmark-icon\" src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/icon/android-chrome-192x192-459.png\" alt=\"Those Blinking LEDs on Your Raspberry Pi Have Special Meanings\"><span class=\"kg-bookmark-author\">It&apos;s FOSS</span><span class=\"kg-bookmark-publisher\">Pratham Patel</span></div></div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-thumbnail\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/thumbnail/debug-raspberry-pi-with-usb-adapter.png\" alt=\"Those Blinking LEDs on Your Raspberry Pi Have Special Meanings\" onerror=\"this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;\"></div></a></figure><p>In the same context, knowing the <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/raspberry-pi-5-pinout/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Raspberry Pi pinout</a> is always helpful.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-bookmark-card\"><a class=\"kg-bookmark-container\" href=\"https://itsfoss.com/raspberry-pi-5-pinout/\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-content\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-title\">Understanding the Raspberry Pi 5 Pin Out</div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-description\">Let&#x2019;s take a closer look at each pin in Raspberry Pi 5 and its specific function to ensure you&#x2019;re well-prepared for your project.</div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-metadata\"><img class=\"kg-bookmark-icon\" src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/icon/android-chrome-192x192-458.png\" alt=\"Those Blinking LEDs on Your Raspberry Pi Have Special Meanings\"><span class=\"kg-bookmark-author\">It&apos;s FOSS</span><span class=\"kg-bookmark-publisher\">Abhishek Kumar</span></div></div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-thumbnail\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/thumbnail/raspberry-pi-5-pinout.png\" alt=\"Those Blinking LEDs on Your Raspberry Pi Have Special Meanings\" onerror=\"this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;\"></div></a></figure><p>What do you think? Have you ever used the Pi&#x2019;s LEDs to diagnose an issue? Drop a comment below and share your experiences.</p>"))) ("Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code" "<img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/automatically-format-code-on-save.webp\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\"><p>Manually formatting code can be tedious, especially in fast-paced or collaborative development environments. </p><p>While consistent formatting is essential for readability and maintainability, doing it by hand slows you down and sometimes leads to inconsistent results across a project.</p><p>In this article, I&#x2019;ll walk you through the steps to configure Visual Studio Code to automatically format your code each time you save a file. </p><p>We&apos;ll use the VS Code extension called <a href=\"https://prettier.io\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Prettier</a>, one of the most widely adopted tools for enforcing code style in JavaScript, TypeScript, and many other languages. </p><p>By the end of this guide, you&apos;ll have a setup that keeps your code clean with zero extra effort.</p><h2 id=\"step-1-install-prettier-extension-in-vs-code\">Step 1: Install Prettier extension in VS Code</h2><p>To start, you&apos;ll need the <strong>Prettier - Code Formatter</strong> extension. This tool supports JavaScript, TypeScript, HTML, CSS, React, Vue, and more.</p><p>Open VS Code, go to the <strong>Extensions</strong> sidebar (or press <code>Ctrl + Shift + X</code>), and search for <a href=\"https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=esbenp.prettier-vscode\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><strong>Prettier</strong></a>.</p><p>Click on <strong>Install</strong> and reload VS Code if prompted.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/prettier-vscode-extension.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1229\" height=\"688\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/prettier-vscode-extension.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/prettier-vscode-extension.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/prettier-vscode-extension.png 1229w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><h2 id=\"step-2-enable-format-on-save\">Step 2: Enable format on save</h2><p>Now that Prettier is installed, let&#x2019;s make it run automatically whenever you save a file.</p><p>Open <strong>Settings</strong> via <code>Ctrl + ,</code> or by going to <strong>File &gt; Preferences &gt; Settings</strong>.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/accessing-settings.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1064\" height=\"959\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/accessing-settings.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/accessing-settings.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/accessing-settings.png 1064w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>In the search bar at the top, type <code>format on save</code> and then Check the box for <strong>Editor: Format On Save</strong>.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/format-on-save.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1391\" height=\"468\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/format-on-save.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/format-on-save.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/format-on-save.png 1391w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>This tells VS Code to auto-format your code whenever you save a file, but that&#x2019;s only part of the setup.</p><h2 id=\"troubleshooting\">Troubleshooting</h2><p>If saving a file doesn&#x2019;t automatically format your code, it&#x2019;s likely due to multiple formatters being installed in VS Code. Here&#x2019;s how to make sure Prettier is set as the default:</p><ul><li>Open any file in VS Code and press <code>Ctrl + Shift + P</code> (or <code>Cmd + Shift + P</code> on Mac) to bring up the Command Palette.</li><li>Type <strong>&#x201C;Format Document&#x201D;</strong> and select the option that appears.</li></ul><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/format-document-1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1072\" height=\"465\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/format-document-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/format-document-1.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/format-document-1.png 1072w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><ul><li>If multiple formatters are available, VS Code will prompt you to choose one.</li></ul><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/configure-formatter.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1110\" height=\"423\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/configure-formatter.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/configure-formatter.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/configure-formatter.png 1110w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><ul><li>Select <strong>&#x201C;Prettier - Code formatter&#x201D;</strong> from the list.</li></ul><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/multiple-formatter.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1139\" height=\"342\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/multiple-formatter.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/multiple-formatter.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/multiple-formatter.png 1139w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>Now try saving your file again. If Prettier is correctly selected, it should instantly reformat the code on save.</p><p>In some cases, you might want to save a file <em>without</em> applying formatting, for example, when working with generated code or temporary formatting quirks. To do that, open the Command Palette again and run <strong>&#x201C;Save Without Formatting.&#x201D;</strong></p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/save-without-format-1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1135\" height=\"411\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/save-without-format-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/save-without-format-1.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/save-without-format-1.png 1135w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><h2 id=\"optional-advanced-configuration\">Optional: Advanced configuration</h2><p>Prettier works well out of the box, but you can customize how it formats your code by adding a <code>.prettierrc</code> configuration file at the root of your project.</p><p>Here&#x2019;s a simple example:</p><pre><code class=\"language-json\">{
  &quot;singleQuote&quot;: true,
  &quot;trailingComma&quot;: &quot;es5&quot;,
  &quot;semi&quot;: false
}
</code></pre><p>This configuration tells Prettier to use single quotes, add trailing commas where valid in ES5 (like in objects and arrays), and omit semicolons at the end of statements.</p><p>There are many other options available such as adjusting print width, tab width, or controlling how JSX and HTML are handled.</p><p>You can find the full list of supported options in <a href=\"https://prettier.io/docs/configuration\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Prettier&#x2019;s documentation</a>, but for most projects, a few key settings in <code>.prettierrc</code> go a long way.</p><h2 id=\"try-it-out\">Try It Out</h2><p>Create or open any file, JavaScript, TypeScript, HTML, etc. Add some poorly formatted code. </p><pre><code class=\"language-html\">&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;style&gt;body{background:#fff;color:#333;font-family:sans-serif}&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;h1&gt;Hello&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;script&gt;document.querySelector(&quot;h1&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;,()=&gt;{alert(&quot;Hello World!&quot;)})&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/html-code-unformatted-1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1268\" height=\"374\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/html-code-unformatted-1.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2025/05/html-code-unformatted-1.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/html-code-unformatted-1.png 1268w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>Then simply save the file (<code>Ctrl + S</code> or <code>Cmd + S</code>), and watch Prettier instantly clean it up.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/saving-unformatter-html-code-file.gif\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"800\" height=\"415\" srcset=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2025/05/saving-unformatter-html-code-file.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/saving-unformatter-html-code-file.gif 800w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>As you can see, Prettier neatly indents and spaces each part of the html code, even across different embedded languages.</p><h2 id=\"wrapping-up\">Wrapping Up</h2><p>It doesn&apos;t matter if <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/vibe-coding-editors/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">you are vibe coding</a> or doing everything on your own, proper formatting is a sign of writing good code.</p><p>We&#x2019;ve already covered the fundamentals of writing clean, consistent code - <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/vs-code-indentation/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">indentation</a>, spacing, and <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/vs-code-word-wrap/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">word wrap</a>, and automatic formatting builds directly on top of those fundamentals.</p><p>Once configured, it removes the need to think about structure while coding, letting you focus on the logic.</p><p>If you&apos;re also wondering how to actually run JavaScript or <a href=\"https://itsfoss.com/vs-code-run-html/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">HTML inside VS Code</a>, we&apos;ve covered that as well, so check those guides if you&apos;re setting up your workflow from scratch.</p><p>If you&#x2019;re not already using automatic formatting, it&#x2019;s worth making part of your workflow. </p><p>And if you use a different tool or approach, I&#x2019;d be interested to hear how you&#x2019;ve set it up, let us know in the comments. &#x1F9D1;&#x200D;&#x1F4BB;</p>" "https://itsfoss.com/vs-code-auto-format-code/" (26665 28343) new 15 nil nil ((title nil "Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code") (description nil "Save time and effort by setting up auto format when you save files in VS Code. Let the code have good vibe.") (link nil "https://itsfoss.com/vs-code-auto-format-code/") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "6814746e3219c9504625fd55") (category nil "VS Code") (creator nil "Abhishek Kumar") (pubDate nil "Sun, 18 May 2025 05:23:03 GMT") (content ((url . "https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/automatically-format-code-on-save.webp") (medium . "image"))) (encoded nil "<img src=\"https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2025/05/automatically-format-code-on-save.webp\" alt=\"Automatically Format Code On File Save in Visual Studio Code\"><p>Manually formatting code can be tedious, especially in fast-paced or collaborative development environments. </p><p>While consistent formatting is essential for readability and maintainability, doing it by hand slows you down and sometimes leads to inconsistent results across a project.</p><p>In this article, I&#x2019;ll walk you through the steps to configure Visual Studio Code to automatically format your code each time you save a file. </p><p>We&apos;ll use the VS Code extension called <a href=\"https://prettier.io\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Prettier</a>, one of the most widely adopted to